            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Arjun Salehi is a product of the Bay Area\u2019s confluence of cultures. Born in Fremont to an Iranian father who fled Tehran after the 1979 revolution and an Indian mother who came to California for graduate school, Arjun\u2019s childhood was a vibrant mix of Persian poetry, Bollywood films, and the scent of saffron rice and cardamom tea. He grew up tinkering with discarded electronics, his natural aptitude for technology pointing him toward a degree in Information Technology at San Jose State.\n\nHis path was rerouted in his second year when his father\u2019s health declined sharply, forcing Arjun to drop out and take a full-time job to help with medical bills. He never returned to college, a fact that remains a quiet point of insecurity. Instead, he built a career from the ground up, starting in help desk support before finding his niche not in coding, but in the tangible, humming world of data centers. As a Data Center Operations Technician, he is one of the unseen hands keeping the digital city alive, maintaining the physical hardware that powers the cloud.\n\nNow 42, Arjun lives a life of routine in a rent-controlled one-bedroom apartment in the Inner Richmond. His day begins before sunrise, catching the 38-Geary bus for the long ride to the data hub. The commute is his time for podcasts on history and tech, a buffer between his quiet home life and the roar of server fans. After a long-term relationship ended last year, his social life has become smaller, revolving around a weekly trivia night at a local pub and occasional dinners with a few trusted colleagues.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco is less about the glitz of tech wealth and more about the city\u2019s grounding reality. He finds peace in long walks through Golden Gate Park and loves the fog-laced quiet of his neighborhood. His dream isn't to launch a startup, but to achieve a sense of lasting security\u2014perhaps owning a small condo someday, a near-impossible goal he still holds onto. More pressingly, he hopes to save enough to finally visit Iran and India, to walk the streets his parents left behind and connect the stories of his youth to the places themselves."
