        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was fourteen, sitting on the floor of the Fremont garage, trying to fix a broken radio. His father sat beside him, watching his hands. As Arjun finally soldered a connection and the speaker crackled to life, his Baba didn't praise the technical skill. Instead, he began reciting a Hafez poem in Farsi, the ancient words a strange and beautiful counterpoint to the smell of electronics. It was the first time Arjun understood that building, fixing, and remembering were all part of the same human impulse.\n\n2.\nThe kitchen table felt like a courtroom. He was nineteen, and the San Jose State tuition bill lay between his parents like an accusation. He saw the worry etched on his mother's face and the quiet shame in his father\u2019s posture, a man whose health was failing. \"I'll drop out for a while,\" Arjun said, the words tasting like ash. \"I'll get a full-time job.\" It wasn\u2019t a sacrifice, but a son's duty. That decision set his path, forging a pragmatist who forever felt he was proving his worth.\n\n3.\nIt was 3 a.m. at his first data center job, a critical server rack down. Senior engineers were baffled remotely. Arjun, then 26 and feeling like an impostor, walked the cold aisle, ignoring the frantic pings and just listening. He heard it\u2014a faint, high-pitched whine from a single faulty power supply. He swapped it, and the system roared back to life. The silence on the comms line was his diploma. That night, he knew he didn't need a degree; he had instincts.\n\n4.\nThe end wasn't a fight, but the quiet click of his apartment door. After ten years, she had handed him back his key. Her parting words, about needing to see the world while he was so rooted, didn't sting as much as the silence that followed. Standing in his living room, surrounded by a future that had just evaporated, he felt a profound stillness. His routines, once a comfort, became his fortress\u2014a structured defense against the quiet emptiness of a life suddenly lived for one.\n\n5.\nA few years ago, on a walk through a fog-soaked Golden Gate Park, he felt adrift. The world was a muffled grey hum. Then, as the mist swirled and thinned, the Conservatory of Flowers emerged, a ghostly, beautiful mirage. He stopped, breathless. He wasn't a founder or an executive; he was just a man on a walk. In that moment, he knew why he stayed. His connection to San Francisco wasn't in the cloud he maintained, but in the grounded, foggy soul of the city itself."
